ğŸ“– **Description:**
    The `bwrap` (bubblewrap) command allows you to run applications in an isolated and secure environment. This means that applications cannot access all parts of the system, improving security. It's like each application runs in an isolated container.

âš™ï¸ **Options:**
    ğŸ”¹ `--ro-bind <source> <destination>` --> ğŸ”’ Mount a directory as read-only inside the bubble.  Source is the original directory, and destination is where it's mounted inside the bubble.
    ğŸ”¹ `--bind <source> <destination>`  --> ğŸ”— Mount a directory as read-write inside the bubble.  Any changes in the destination are also applied to the source.
    ğŸ”¹ `--tmpfs <destination>` --> ğŸ“ Create a temporary directory inside the bubble. When the application finishes, all data in that directory is lost.
    ğŸ”¹ `--unshare-all` -->  Isolate all namespaces (like network, PID, etc.).
    ğŸ”¹ `--chdir <path>` --> ğŸ“‚ Change the working directory inside the bubble.

ğŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ bwrap --ro-bind /usr /usr -- /usr/bin/firefox

    ğŸ”¹ Run Firefox in a bubble with read-only access to `/usr`.

    $ bwrap --tmpfs /tmp -- bash

    ğŸ”¹ Open a shell in a bubble where the `/tmp` directory is a temporary directory.

âœ… **Simple Example:**

